The tarragon plant contains numerous coumarins, mainly herniarin (
 Figure 2), as well as coumarin, scopoletin, scoparone, dracumerin, artemidine, esculetin, esculin, and capillarin. The total amount of coumarins in the herb is over 1.0%. The biosynthesis of these compounds begins at an early stage of plant development; therefore, in three-month-old specimens, the coumarin content may even reach 1.3%. The maximum level of this group of compounds has been found in five-year-old plants (
 Aglarova et al., 2008; 
 Bhutia and Valant-vetschera, 2008; 
 Obolskiy et al., 2011; 
 Talbi et al., 2016; 
 Mumivand et al., 2017; 
 Bussmann et al., 2020; 
 Sharopov et al., 2020).
